stories: In optical neural networks (ONNs), light amplitudes are modulated at theinput and detected at the output. However, the light phases are ignored,although they can also carry information for computing. To address thisissue, this paper proposes a framework called Oplixnet that compresses theareas of ONNs by modulating input image data into the amplitudes and phaseparts of light signals. The input and output parts of the ONNs are redesignedto make full use of both amplitude and phase information. Moreover, mutuallearning across different ONN structures is introduced to maintain accuracy.Experimental results demonstrate that the proposed framework significantlyreduces the areas of ONNs with accuracy within an acceptable range. Forexample, 75.03% area is reduced with a 0.33% accuracy decrease on fullyconnected neural network (FCNN) and 74.88% area is reduced with a 2.38%accuracy decrease on ResNet-32.

In optical neural networks (ONNs), input data is modulated into both the amplitudes and phases of light signals, while output data is detected. However, the light phases are often ignored, even though they can carry additional information for computing. To address this issue, a framework called Oplixnet is proposed. This framework compresses the areas of ONNs by using both amplitude and phase information from input and output data. Additionally, mutual learning across different ONN structures is introduced to maintain accuracy. Experimental results show that the proposed framework significantly reduces the areas of ONNs while maintaining an acceptable range of accuracy. For example, 75.03% area is reduced with a 0.33% accuracy decrease on a fully connected neural network (FCNN) and 74.88% area is reduced with a 2.38% accuracy decrease on ResNet-32.

Optical neural networks (ONNs) are a type of neural network that uses light signals to transmit data. However, they only use the amplitudes of the light signals and ignore the phases. This means that they are not fully utilizing the information available in the light signals. To address this issue, a new framework called Oplixnet has been proposed. This framework compresses the areas of ONNs by using both the amplitudes and phases of the input and output data. Additionally, mutual learning across different ONN structures is introduced to maintain accuracy. This means that Oplixnet can reduce the areas of ONNs while still maintaining a good level of accuracy. For example, it can reduce the areas of FCNN and ResNet-32 by 75.03% and 74.88%, respectively, while only decreasing the accuracy by 0.33% and 2.38%, respectively.
